bib.title: High Resolution Investigation Of Resonances In 19F*

free_txt: BP
BP: Ph.D. thesis 45 degree data were added.
To obtain practical computation of R-matrix cross
sections, the multi-level, multi-channel computer
program MULTI was written. Nuclear potential phase
shifts are approximated by hard sphere values; these
values are fixed by determining the interaction radii
aa. For the present case, phase shifts for the
elastic channels are the most critical, since
resonance shapes and the magnitude of the cross
section generated depend upon them. For protons, the
values chosen was aa=5.25 fm. The relation aa =
r0(A1**1/3 + A2**1/3) yields r0=1.45 fm. These were
used to assign the values to the aas for the reaction
products.
The charged particle cryostat provided only a
single solid state detector at the fixed angle of 135
degrees.
The yield curve was taken in 500-eV proton energy
steps. Above threshold, the 18O(p,n)18F yield was
monitored with the 20 degrees neutron collimator.
After the entire yield curve was taken at 135 degrees,
the cryostat was rotated 180 degrees to place the
detection angle at 45 degrees. Preliminary
calculations indicated that those levels prominent in
the elastic yield at 135 degrees would also be
detectable in the elastic yield at 45 degrees, and
that the shapes of these levels would immediately
discriminate d-wave resonances from f-wave
resonances. These resonant shapes were observed by
using the method of  data acquisition described by
Seibel. In this method, the energy of the accelerator
is modulated allowing up to 20 keV of data to be
taken at one time.
